    faq: [
      { q: 'What is the best golf bag for walking?', a: "The Sun Mountain 2.5+ at 2.8 lbs is the lightest full-feature carry bag for walkers — dual straps, 14 dividers, and a hip belt rangefinder pocket. If you want retractable stand legs for versatility at the range and on walking courses, the Titleist Players 4 StaDry is the premium pick at 4.6 lbs. The weight difference (1.8 lbs empty, 3-4 lbs loaded) is noticeable over 18 hilly holes but negligible on flat courses." },
      { q: 'Can I use a stand bag on a golf cart?', a: "Yes — stand bags fit on carts, but they sit higher and less securely than cart bags designed for the cart strap channel. The stand legs can also interfere with cart bag wells on some carts. If you ride 80%+ of your rounds, a cart bag gives you better stability, more pocket space, and easier club access. If you split between walking and riding, a stand bag is the better compromise." },
          { q: 'What is the lightest golf carry bag?', a: 'The Sun Mountain 2.5+ is one of the lightest at 2.8 lbs empty. Loaded with 14 clubs and typical accessories (rangefinder, balls, tees, towel, water bottle), expect 18-22 lbs total. Among full 14-club stand bags, anything under 5 lbs empty is considered lightweight. The loaded weight matters more than the empty weight — a 3 lb bag with heavy clubs weighs the same as a 5 lb bag with lighter clubs.' },
  
      { q: 'How many pockets does a golf bag need?', a: 'Five is the minimum for a full round: apparel/rain jacket, balls, accessories (tees, markers, divot tool), valuables (phone, wallet, keys), and a water bottle pocket. Premium bags add a dedicated rangefinder pocket (worth having) and a cooler pocket (nice for summer). More than 8 pockets is diminishing returns — you spend more time looking for things than benefiting from the organization.' },
      { q: 'Is a 14-way divider better than 4-way?', a: 'For most golfers, yes. A 14-way divider prevents clubs from tangling, protects graphite shafts from contact damage, and makes it faster to pull the right club mid-round. The tradeoff is weight — 14-way bags are 0.5-1 lb heavier. The only golfers who benefit from 4-way dividers are ultralight walkers who prioritize every ounce and carry fewer than 14 clubs.' },
      { q: 'Should I buy a waterproof golf bag?', a: 'If you play in the Midwest, Northeast, Pacific Northwest, or UK — yes. Morning dew alone is enough to soak a non-waterproof bag by hole 3. Waterproof bags cost $30-50 more and add minimal weight. The Callaway Chev Dry ($129) is the most affordable waterproof option. In dry climates like Arizona or Southern California, waterproofing is unnecessary.' },
    ],
