    pageType: 'comparison',
    tag: 'COMPARISON',
    quickAnswerProduct: 'titleist-pro-v1',
    emoji: '⛳',
    thumb: 'olive',
    words: '1,900',
    datePublished: '2025-12-28',
    dateModified: '2026-04-23',
    updateLog: [
      { date: 'Apr 22, 2026', note: 'Annual freshness review — verified pricing and availability.' },
    ],
    title: 'Pro V1 vs Chrome Soft — Which Golf Ball Should You Play?',
    titleDisplay: 'Titleist Pro V1 vs Callaway Chrome Soft',
    bottomLine: 'The <strong>Pro V1</strong> is the better golf ball for golfers with 90+ mph swing speed — more distance, more greenside spin, tighter consistency. The <strong>Chrome Soft</strong> is the better choice for golfers with 80-90 mph swing speed or anyone who prioritizes soft feel above all else. At $55 vs $40 per dozen, the Chrome Soft also wins on value.',
    description: 'Titleist Pro V1 vs Callaway Chrome Soft — distance, spin, feel, durability, and which premium golf ball is right for your swing speed in 2026.',
    excerpt: 'Pro V1 vs Chrome Soft head-to-head — distance at multiple swing speeds, greenside spin, feel, and value analysis.',
    ogImage: 'https://www.cubicalgolfer.com/images/thumbnails/pro-v1-vs-chrome-soft-thumb.webp',
    thumbnail: '/images/thumbnails/pro-v1-vs-chrome-soft-thumb.webp',
    intro: "The Pro V1 ($55/dozen) and Chrome Soft ($40/dozen) are both premium urethane-cover golf balls competing for a spot in your bag. We played 10 rounds with each, alternating every other round, to compare distance, spin, feel, and value across multiple swing speeds.",
    toc: ['Comparison table', 'Distance at 94 mph and 86 mph', 'Greenside spin', 'Putting feel', 'Durability', 'Value per round', 'Who should play which', 'FAQ'],
    sections: [
      { h2: 'Quick Comparison', body: "Both are 3-piece urethane-cover tour balls. The Pro V1 has 87 compression; the Chrome Soft has 75 compression. That 12-point gap is the key — it determines which swing speed each ball is optimized for." },
      { h2: 'Distance — Pro V1 Wins at 94 mph, Closer at 86 mph', body: "At 94 mph driver speed: Pro V1 carried 226 yards. Chrome Soft carried 220 yards. A 6-yard gap — meaningful over 14 drives per round.\n\nAt 86 mph driver speed (our playing partner): Pro V1 carried 208 yards. Chrome Soft carried 205 yards. A 3-yard gap — much smaller because the softer Chrome Soft compresses more efficiently at lower speeds.\n\nOn 7-iron at 88 mph: Pro V1 carried 155 yards. Chrome Soft carried 150 yards. A consistent 5-yard gap.\n\nThe pattern: the faster you swing, the more the Pro V1 pulls ahead. At 95+ mph, the Pro V1 distance advantage is significant. At 80-85 mph, the gap narrows to where it may not affect your club selection.\n\nWinner: Pro V1 — but the gap shrinks at lower swing speeds." },
      { h2: 'Greenside Spin — Pro V1 by a Clear Margin', body: "On 60-yard pitch shots: Pro V1 checked within 2 feet of landing. Chrome Soft checked at 4 feet. On 30-yard chips: Pro V1 grabbed immediately. Chrome Soft released 12-18 inches more.\n\nThe Pro V1 urethane cover generates more friction against wedge grooves. The higher compression core also produces more spin on partial swings. For golfers who rely on greenside spin to get up and down, the Pro V1 is measurably better.\n\nThe Chrome Soft is not bad around the greens — it is a urethane ball that spins more than any ionomer-cover budget ball. But head-to-head against the Pro V1, the spin gap is clear and consistent.\n\nWinner: Pro V1 — checks 2 feet closer on pitch shots." },
      { h2: 'Putting Feel — Chrome Soft Is Softer', body: "The Chrome Soft produces a muffled thud off the putter — the softest feel of any premium ball we have tested. There is almost no click. For golfers who hate the clicky sound of firmer balls, the Chrome Soft is the answer.\n\nThe Pro V1 has a soft click — muted but responsive. You feel the distance in your hands. On 25-foot lag putts, the Pro V1 gave us better speed calibration because the feedback was more informative.\n\nThis is pure preference. If you want the softest possible feel, Chrome Soft wins. If you want soft feel WITH distance feedback, Pro V1 wins.\n\nWinner: Depends on preference — Chrome Soft for pure softness, Pro V1 for feedback." },
      { h2: 'Durability', body: "Pro V1: minor scuffing after bunker shots, maintained performance through 18 holes, significant wear by hole 27.\n\nChrome Soft: scuffing appeared earlier — visible marks by hole 12. The softer cover is more susceptible to abrasion. Performance was not noticeably affected through 18 but the ball looked rougher sooner.\n\nWinner: Pro V1 — slightly more durable cover." },
      { h2: 'Value Per Round', body: "Pro V1 at $55/dozen: $4.58 per ball. Losing 2 per round costs $9.16 in lost balls = ~$14 per round total.\n\nChrome Soft at $40/dozen: $3.33 per ball. Losing 2 costs $6.66 = ~$10 per round total.\n\nThe Chrome Soft saves $4 per round — $100 over a 25-round season. For golfers who lose 3+ balls per round, the savings are even larger.\n\nWinner: Chrome Soft — $15/dozen cheaper, saves $100+ per season." },
      { h2: 'Who Should Play Which', body: "Play the Pro V1 if: your driver swing speed is 90+ mph, you shoot under 90, you value greenside spin for scoring, and you lose fewer than 3 balls per round. The higher compression optimizes at faster speeds and the spin advantage translates to saved strokes around the green.\n\nPlay the Chrome Soft if: your swing speed is 80-90 mph, you prioritize soft feel above all else, you want a premium ball at $15/dozen less than the Pro V1, or you lose 3+ balls per round and want to reduce cost without dropping to an ionomer-cover ball.\n\nThe compromise pick: Srixon Q-Star Tour ($35/dozen) — 72 compression sits between the Pro V1 (87) and Chrome Soft (75) with urethane cover spin at a budget price.",
        affiliateKey: 'titleist-pro-v1' },
    ],
    comparisonTable: { headers: ['Golf Ball', 'Price', 'Compression', 'Carry (94mph)', 'Rating'], rows: [
      { affiliateKey: 'titleist-pro-v1', name: 'Titleist Pro V1', bestFor: '90+ mph', price: '~$55/dz', feature1: '4.9/5 ★', feature2: '87', winner: true },
      { affiliateKey: 'callaway-chrome-soft', name: 'Callaway Chrome Soft', bestFor: '80-90 mph', price: '~$40/dz', feature1: '4.5/5 ★', feature2: '75', winner: false },
      { affiliateKey: 'srixon-q-star-tour', name: 'Srixon Q-Star Tour', bestFor: 'Best Value', price: '~$35/dz', feature1: '4.5/5 ★', feature2: '72', winner: false },
    ] },
    faq: [
      { q: 'Pro V1 or Chrome Soft for a 15 handicap?', a: 'Depends on swing speed. 90+ mph: Pro V1. 80-90 mph: Chrome Soft. Under 80 mph: neither — use the Srixon Q-Star Tour or Callaway Supersoft for better compression at your speed.' },
      { q: 'Is the Pro V1 worth $15 more per dozen?', a: 'If you swing 90+ mph and shoot under 90, the spin and consistency justify $15. If you shoot 95+, the performance gap disappears in inconsistent ball striking — save the $15.' },
      { q: 'Which is softer off the putter?', a: 'Chrome Soft — noticeably softer with almost no click. Pro V1 is soft but provides more distance feedback. Personal preference determines the winner.' },
      { q: 'Can I mix Pro V1 and Chrome Soft during a round?', a: 'Technically yes, but not recommended. Each ball has different spin and distance characteristics. Switching mid-round makes club selection inconsistent. Pick one and commit for the round.' },
    ],
    sources: [{ label: 'Titleist — Pro V1 Specs', url: 'https://www.titleist.com/golf-balls/pro-v1' }, { label: 'Callaway — Chrome Soft Technology', url: 'https://www.callawaygolf.com/golf-balls/' }],
